The Grow with Data Youth Foundation (GWDYF), has commenced free training of 30 female youths, on future informed financial decision to reduce poverty gap in Northern region. Nnenna Mosugu, Executive Director, at the inauguration of the 3-day training in Yola said, it is aimed at exposing participants horizon on income generation, saving, ICT and budget planning for job creation. The non-profit organization had so far set up eight (8), financial literacy clubs in  secondary schools in the state adding, students knowledge on financial matters has been tremendously improved. “Investing in female education yields exceptionally high social and economic returns, giving them opportunities to be employable and close the poverty gap. “Women literacy in the Northeast is among the lowest in the country at 28%, compared to their male counterpart at 66% and women from the south eastern regions at 84%. “This puts women in these regions at a disadvantage with respect to financial sustainability and employment opportunities. “Creating access to vocational and entrepreneurial programme becomes inevitable to navigate critical areas of concern such as gender equality and women empowerment. The program implemented by MENTOS International, to cover the 21 LGAs is expected to change women view toward contributing to their families, community and the economic growth of their immediate environment. “To enlighten the participants on skills that have been identified as being crucial to master in preparation for success in a rapidly changing, digital society and with the current trend of Work from Home (WFH).” Janet Innocent, a beneficiary of the training, lauded the founders of the training for knowledge she acquired on Graphic Design, Blogging, and Web design. Areas explored by resource persons at the training for the participants (The Money Smart Lady) involved Video editing and Photography. 